lays, and prose by writers such as Shakespeare, Scudéry, Boileau, and Donne, as well as popular materials including pamphlets, ballads, and broadsides, she examines the impact of rapid urbanization on cultural production. Newman shows how changing demographics and technological development altered these two emerging urban centers in which new forms of cultural capital were produced and new modes of sociability and representation were articulated.Cultural Capitals is a fascinating work of literary and cultural history that redefines our conception of when the modern city came to be and brings early modern London and Paris alive in all their splendor, squalor, and richness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSociology, UrbanzEnglandzLondon. 0aSociology, UrbanzFrancezParis. 0aSpatial behaviorzEnglandzLondon. 0aSpatial behaviorzFrancezParis. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aAscham, Roger.  aBernini, Gianlorenzo.  aBosse, Abraham.  aCade's rebellion.  aCarroll, William.  aChaucer, Geoffrey.  aDewald, Jonathan.  aFerguson, Frances.  aHarvey, Gabriel.  aHorace.  aHoward, Jean.  aJerusalem.  aJouhaud, Christian.  aKermode, Frank.  aLatour, Bruno.  aLibanius.  aLougée, Carolyn.  aNuremberg Chronicle.  aaesthetic.  aantiquarianism.  aantiquities.  abawd.  abook trade.  abridges.  aconsumer goods.  aconsumerism.  aconversation.  acultural materialism.  adisplacement.  aengravings.  aentrepreneurialism.  afootnotes, scholarly.  agallantry.  aglobalization.  aguidebooks.  aidentity politics.  aindividualism.  amanuscript culture.  amazarinades.  ametropolitan literature.  amodernity.  anew historicism.  aorient, the.  aovidianism.  aparish registers.  aperipatetic.  aphonophobia.  apoststructuralism.  a